1. What is a Promise?

A Promise is an object that represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation.

Think of it like ordering food:

🍕 You place an order.
⏳ The restaurant prepares it.
✅ You either receive the food or ❌ your order is cancelled.
Promise States

A Promise has 3 states:

Pending
   │
   ├──► Fulfilled (Success)
   │
   └──► Rejected (Failure)
Pending → Initial state
Fulfilled → Operation completed successfully
Rejected → Operation failed
2. Creating a Promise
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {

    let success = true;

    if (success) {
        resolve("Operation Successful");
    } else {
        reject("Operation Failed");
    }

});

Here:

resolve() → Success
reject() → Failure
3. Using .then()

.then() is executed when the Promise is fulfilled.

const promise = new Promise((resolve) => {

    resolve("Payment Successful");

});

promise.then((message) => {
    console.log(message);
});
Output
Payment Successful
4. Using .catch()

.catch() is executed when the Promise is rejected.

const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {

    reject("Payment Failed");

});

promise
    .then((message) => {
        console.log(message);
    })
    .catch((error) => {
        console.log(error);
    });
Output
Payment Failed
5. Using .finally()

.finally() always runs, whether the Promise succeeds or fails.

const promise = new Promise((resolve) => {

    resolve("Order Completed");

});

promise
    .then((message) => {
        console.log(message);
    })
    .finally(() => {
        console.log("Thank you for using our service.");
    });
Output
Order Completed
Thank you for using our service.
6. Simulating an API Call
function fetchUser() {

    return new Promise((resolve) => {

        setTimeout(() => {
            resolve("User Data Loaded");
        }, 2000);

    });

}

fetchUser().then((data) => {
    console.log(data);
});
Output
(wait 2 seconds)

User Data Loaded
7. Handling Errors
function login(isValid) {

    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {

        if (isValid) {
            resolve("Login Successful");
        } else {
            reject("Invalid Username or Password");
        }

    });

}

login(false)
    .then((message) => {
        console.log(message);
    })
    .catch((error) => {
        console.log(error);
    });
Output
Invalid Username or Password
8. Promise Chaining ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Instead of nested callbacks:

login()
    .then(() => verifyOTP())
    .then(() => transferMoney())
    .then(() => console.log("Transaction Completed"))
    .catch((error) => console.log(error));

This is much cleaner than Callback Hell.

Real-World Example – ATM
function verifyPIN() {

    return new Promise((resolve) => {

        setTimeout(() => {
            resolve("PIN Verified");
        }, 1000);

    });

}

function checkBalance() {

    return new Promise((resolve) => {

        setTimeout(() => {
            resolve("Balance: ₹10,000");
        }, 1000);

    });

}

verifyPIN()
    .then((message) => {
        console.log(message);
        return checkBalance();
    })
    .then((balance) => {
        console.log(balance);
    })
    .catch((error) => {
        console.log(error);
    });
Output
PIN Verified
Balance: ₹10,000
Promise vs Callback
Callback	Promise
Nested code	Cleaner code
Callback Hell	Promise Chaining
Harder to maintain	Easier to read
Difficult error handling	.catch() handles errors
Common Mistakes
❌ Forgetting return

Wrong:

function getData() {
    new Promise((resolve) => {
        resolve("Data");
    });
}

Correct:

function getData() {
    return new Promise((resolve) => {
        resolve("Data");
    });
}
❌ Not Handling Errors

Wrong:

login(false).then((msg) => console.log(msg));

Correct:

login(false)
    .then((msg) => console.log(msg))
    .catch((err) => console.log(err));
